segments.text: Yes, it was great, but I just think, you know, I go to bed at night sometimes, I just think how wonderful it's going to be that he's still alive and vigorous and can have interchanges with our society.
Yeah, yeah.
And that's what he's going to do.
He likes to come on the quids of the library.
Right.
And he has come to settle in here.
Well, he really does love it.
He likes it, that's right.
Yeah, he does.
He does have a nice place to stay, too.
Yeah.
So, November's dedication.
November 5th and 6th.
What impact do you think, this is a very broad closing comment, what impact do you think the press has, what they have, what have been its high points, low points, what do you see as...
Is it in trouble?
No, I don't think so.
You know, I don't really see low points.
I guess maybe I'm an optimist.
But I see nothing but high points in the West.
And I have not ever been discouraged.
We've had the people, most of our presidents have been
interested in the press and have carried it forward.
I guess we had one president that wasn't so interested.
That's all right.
But we managed to, if there was a low point, I guess maybe that was it.
But that was a little discouraging at times.
He didn't do anything to hurt us.
He didn't do anything to help us, but he didn't do anything to hurt us.
And now we've got Bowen who gives away books at our luncheons every day and every football game.
And those are wonderful things.
And that's kind of what I envision.
Those things, those books have Texas A&M on them and they're in people's bookshelves and libraries forever.
You know, that was one of Frank's letters, and in that Type 22 article he did, he carefully explained why a press is important at the University of New York.
Right.
And I think that needs to be reiterated over and over again.
I do, too.
That's one of the things I hope to do with this book.
Right.
I agree with you.
Because it is a, they are wonderful things that, you know,
People, I envy people that read more than I do, and most people do.
Because they do, they just get a lot out of life.
But it's very, it's just wonderful that they do.
Do you think the, in terms of, this is really up your ball,
In terms of the kinds of books we publish, are you satisfied?
Yes.
Oh, yeah.
I'm very, very pleased with what we've published.
You think Frank is still right on with the regional Texas thrust?
Yeah, I do.
And I think he'd be very proud of our selection every year.
I can't think of a single year that he wouldn't have been proud of.
That's why I'm really trying to get this down very tightly in the early phase because I think whatever he's set down, that's the way it's been.
It really is.
I think so too.
It's fallen through very, very much.
I think so too.
We're proud of all of our authors.
Isn't our friend Frank Vandiver?
Yes.
He's got another book coming.
Have you seen his book yet?
No, I have not.
I use Frank's book, Blood Brothers, I guess, in my classes.
I've got two of these big survey classes.
350 students in one, 150 in the other.
I use Frank's Blood Brothers.
I used to ask him to come in and lecture.
He loves to, but now he's got a tape.
Oh, really?
Oh, he is great.
I just think he is so wonderful.
I'm going to try to talk to him, too, because he...
He was supposed to be involved with Wardlaw before the press came in.
Yes, he was.
He knew him in Austin.
Yeah, his father taught him.
His favorite father taught him.
And I'm sure he would have said, nah, he's not coming over to the college station.
You know, it was like that.
There was no way you'd get Ward Lovett.
How about the region from the press now?
Was that a pretty happy accord?
Oh, sure.
They were sensitive and understanding?
They were.
Several of them.
I had Vandiver come to the last Board of Regents meeting and Tom Rotell.
I put it on.
I used it as an excuse for his new book that's coming out.
And he brought books for all the regents.
He signed them all and gave each one of them one.
And several of the regents came up to me afterwards and said, what a nice thing to do.
And thanked me for calling this to their attention.
So it was, yes, they liked the press.
So that was good.
Well, wouldn't you like it?
That's right.
That's the good point.
The kind of books we publish are certainly
They're not controversial in any way at all.
They're just all scholarly books.
I mean, I know I've been over the back of the Committee of the Press now.
That's a win-win situation.
Well, yeah.
I know Clint Phillips always said, you know, that's one of the happiest things I've ever done in Texas A&M is be on the Press Committee.
It really is.
Haskell Monroe said that, too.
Haskell's moving back, I guess.
I know it.
Yes, I do know it.
Catch him.
I'm very excited about that sort of thing.
Yeah, that's great.
Yes, by all means, be sure and talk to him.
He's somebody that's, bless his heart, you know, when they tore the old press building, the old border, he just built it down after the fire.
He gets in there and, you know, gets bricks and pieces of the building or something.
Well, he got one of these big old weights in the windows, you know, the array of the windows.
That big...
round iron thing that goes up and think, well, he got one of those for me.
He brought it home to my house.
Of course, I never would have thought of having one of those.
Well, I have one.
You still have it.
I still have it.
Sure, I do.
And I think of Haskell every time I see that.
I told him when we tore down the Warefield house that I'm going to get a brick from there.
I wonder if he still hauls those bricks around.
Sure, he does.
I know he does, because he keeps them.
Well, any last words?
